WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.040
Alright, thank you. Hello, everybody. And, yeah, I'd like to join Marlee and other presenters

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:18.600
in thanking rstudio and Phil and others into putting this session together. You know, this

00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:22.719
is my favorite community, R in Pharma, and I'm glad to be here today. And also thank

00:00:22.719 --> 00:00:28.559
you for the opportunity to talk about R in Janssen Drug Discovery Statistics. So my name

00:00:28.559 --> 00:00:33.720
is Volha Tryputsen, and I work as a principal statistician in the Department of Translational

00:00:33.720 --> 00:00:40.040
Medicine and Early Development Statistics at Janssen. So what do we do at Janssen? Well,

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:46.639
at Janssen, we are guided by our mission of blending heart, science, and ingenuity to

00:00:46.639 --> 00:00:51.799
profoundly change the trajectory of health for humanity. And we discover and develop

00:00:51.799 --> 00:01:00.680
drugs which, you know, treat or lead to prevent some of the world's devastating diseases.

00:01:00.680 --> 00:01:05.919
So how do we discover and develop drugs, right? Well, the process is quite complex, but it

00:01:05.919 --> 00:01:11.720
roughly can be broken down into two parts, preclinical drug discovery and development

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:17.360
efforts and clinical. And I think clinical drug discovery, drug development gets a lot

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:23.120
of spotlight, whether preclinical phase is not as commonly talked about. So I'd like

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:28.519
to take a couple of minutes and to give you in a nutshell what that really means to discover

00:01:28.519 --> 00:01:34.879
a drug, right? So it all starts with choosing which disease are you after, right? And then

00:01:34.879 --> 00:01:40.080
after you do that, you identify the target that you're going to try to pursue. Once you

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:46.360
have that in place, you're trying to screen possible compounds or even engineer a new

00:01:46.360 --> 00:01:51.080
compound, they're going to bind to your target. And once that is done, you basically study

00:01:51.080 --> 00:01:56.360
that, that, you know, relationship or that activity that is happening between your compounds

00:01:56.360 --> 00:02:01.559
and target. And you might want to optimize it and look at it at many, many angles. But

00:02:01.559 --> 00:02:05.959
what happens at the end, you select a subset of compounds that you're going to be moving

00:02:05.959 --> 00:02:11.119
forward into other subset of studies. And once you have your subset of compounds, you

00:02:11.119 --> 00:02:17.240
would further test them for efficacy and safety using in vitro, which is outside of

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:22.360
your, you know, living, living body sort of experiments, which could be testing those

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:28.720
compounds and tissue and cell lines. And then also in vivo experiments where you test your

00:02:28.720 --> 00:02:34.440
compounds in a living organism. And then, you know, once that is done, you're basically

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:41.639
ready to move your final compound into, you know, enemy phase, which is naming it for

00:02:41.639 --> 00:02:47.759
a new molecular entity. And that's sort of complete your preclinical drug discovery process.

00:02:47.759 --> 00:02:54.199
But as you can see, it's, it's very, very involved and, you know, very, very, very multifaceted.

00:02:54.199 --> 00:02:59.960
So I work for, for drug discovery statistic group that basically supports all of these

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:06.320
different drug discovery efforts across different therapeutic areas, whether it's neuroscience,

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:12.199
oncology, immunology, infectious diseases, vaccines. And yeah, we do a lot of work working

00:03:12.199 --> 00:03:17.240
with the scientists. So what our department does, it's obviously bringing mathematical

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:25.279
and statistical rigor into building this drug discovery pipeline and also for decision making.

00:03:25.320 --> 00:03:33.039
Right. And so how do we do it? Well, you know, we take the body of data, a lot of studies

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:41.360
that biologists have conducted. And, you know, one of the aspects for us is obviously designing

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:47.279
those studies and work on design of experiments. But also the heavy task for us is to analyze

00:03:47.279 --> 00:03:52.919
all of the data. Right. So we put the data into this sausage making machine, right, called

00:03:52.919 --> 00:03:59.320
statistics. We add some magic to it and voila, we get a p-value. Right. Of course, I'm joking.

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:06.320
It's not as, as, as, you know, as it is on this slide. But instead of magic, we obviously

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:12.240
have a lot of math and statistics within our sausage making machine. Right. And p-value

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:18.320
is one of the things, but it's never the only one. And we accompany all of our findings

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:24.839
with, you know, a lot of different tables, figures, graphical representation, and a lot,

00:04:24.839 --> 00:04:30.079
a lot of different reports. Right. But where I'm trying to go with all of this is that,

00:04:30.079 --> 00:04:35.160
you know, we have this process in place for analyzing this data. But what's really great

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:41.279
is that this whole process is driven by R. Right. In drug discovery statistics department

00:04:41.279 --> 00:04:46.480
at Janssen, we heavily rely on R and RStudio products. And this is what my presentation

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:52.519
is about. So how do we use our capabilities and what do we do with R in drug discovery

00:04:52.519 --> 00:05:00.399
statistics? Well, the most important one is our portfolio support. So we use R extensively

00:05:00.399 --> 00:05:06.640
to analyze a lot of our studies. So when I was thinking how to best kind of present what

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:12.000
do we do with R, I thought about splitting all the stuff that we do into this four different

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:17.359
spheres. Right. So first and foremost is our general practices. Right. The majority

00:05:17.359 --> 00:05:26.000
of us use RStudio and we do it, we use it locally and we also use it off the server.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:31.279
And the server RStudio capabilities are great because what they help us to do is share our

00:05:31.279 --> 00:05:38.079
projects and our different study analysis between ourselves within the group and help

00:05:38.079 --> 00:05:43.200
us to collaborate in this in this manner. But also we've been tapping lately in a powerful

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:47.839
computing capabilities of RStudio server as well for our analysis, but also for shiny

00:05:47.839 --> 00:05:54.239
app development. We all use Git in Bitbucket. So Bitbucket is our local GitHub, we call

00:05:54.239 --> 00:05:59.440
it, which, of course, ensures traceability and transparency of everything that we do,

00:05:59.440 --> 00:06:07.320
but also plays a big role in collaboration and code sharing. We extensively use R packages.

00:06:07.399 --> 00:06:14.600
We create our own, whether they're internal and external for, of course, organizing our

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:21.079
own code, but also for sharing our methodologies with others, which, of course, speaks to the

00:06:21.079 --> 00:06:25.880
rigor and innovation that R packages bring to the whole drug discovery statistics space.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:35.799
We also start packaging our standardized analysis workflow that we actually use to

00:06:35.799 --> 00:06:42.040
create shiny apps into packages as well. And that's, again, an easy way to share your code,

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:49.480
but also makes it easy to troubleshoot or to bring changes that might need to be implemented

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:58.200
if the opportunity comes. We also use R packages for packaging basically templates for R Markdown,

00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:04.839
which I'm going to discuss next. R Markdown reports, something that we simply can't survive

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:12.679
these days. So we extensively use R Markdown reports for a lot of stuff. I think in 2019,

00:07:12.679 --> 00:07:19.559
or maybe at the end of that year, there was a big effort in a department to create one standardized

00:07:19.559 --> 00:07:25.399
parameterized R Markdown template, which kind of incorporates the set expectation between

00:07:25.399 --> 00:07:30.679
ourselves, the decision of how we want to report our statistics, but also between our clients,

00:07:30.679 --> 00:07:36.839
our biologists, and whoever we work with. So what happens last year is we decided to make

00:07:37.399 --> 00:07:44.279
that parameterized general template more specific to therapeutic area that we work with. For instance,

00:07:44.279 --> 00:07:51.160
I mainly support oncology. So we really customized that template that we created first into oncology

00:07:51.160 --> 00:07:56.600
settings, which is really cool because we can customize it whenever we want it, but it also

00:07:56.600 --> 00:08:01.640
brings consistency to all the analysis that we do within oncology drug discovery space,

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:10.920
and obviously speaks to reproducible nature of our research. My favorite and everybody's favorite

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:21.239
are Shiny apps. We do a lot of them. We put them together ourselves. And for some of them,

00:08:21.239 --> 00:08:26.920
we have our developers helping us as well. When I was thinking how to present the Shiny apps,

00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:32.039
it just would have, you know, we can talk about them the whole day, but I basically put everything

00:08:32.039 --> 00:08:36.440
that we do in terms of our Shiny into three buckets. So the first set of applications that

00:08:36.440 --> 00:08:43.400
we develop for drug discovery kind of goes into the bucket of data manipulation. So that could be

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:48.840
anything from, you know, taking different data files that scientists have coming from different

00:08:48.840 --> 00:08:53.640
software that they're using and putting them into Shiny and, you know, mapping the data,

00:08:53.640 --> 00:09:01.719
merging the files, doing some other preprocessing, and then basically exporting some other data file

00:09:01.719 --> 00:09:05.479
type that they need, the scientists need to put into another software or something like that,

00:09:05.479 --> 00:09:10.679
right? So it could be an array of things that we can do with data, which is great that we can

00:09:10.679 --> 00:09:16.919
use Shiny for that because it really eliminates any copy paste or editing error and, you know,

00:09:16.919 --> 00:09:21.719
gives us so much confidence that nothing like that has happened while we're preprocessing

00:09:21.719 --> 00:09:26.520
and manipulating our data. So once we have the data in the right form and shape, the next thing

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:32.760
that we do in statistics is obviously take a closer look at the data and we call it EDA. So

00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:38.200
another set of Shiny applications that we have developed kind of go into that bucket where

00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:42.840
they have to do with data visualization and exploration of your data, which is super important

00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:49.719
and bringing efficiency in that space kind of talks to having a more thorough research

00:09:49.719 --> 00:09:54.440
and obviously, you know, a richer body of evidence when it comes to data exploration.

00:09:55.239 --> 00:10:01.640
And then the last bucket is basically apps that have to do with statistical analysis,

00:10:02.440 --> 00:10:08.599
right? And here we've developed standardized workflows for a particular analysis that

00:10:08.599 --> 00:10:14.840
scientists are doing repeatedly. A lot of those apps have exportable markdown report,

00:10:14.840 --> 00:10:21.239
whether it's PDF, you know, Word or HTML, you name it. And this brings major efficiencies in our

00:10:21.239 --> 00:10:26.039
space because of automation of those repeated tasks and analysis and report generation.

00:10:26.679 --> 00:10:32.520
And of course, because of RStudio Connect capabilities, we can easily deploy the apps

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:39.559
and share them with our colleagues in biology. So, you know, four of these things, general

00:10:39.559 --> 00:10:47.000
practices, our Shiny apps and R packages and R markdown report help us tremendously in a portfolio

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:53.559
development space. But what else we're doing with R? Well, I have the second part where, which I

00:10:53.559 --> 00:10:59.799
call innovation, right? So what do I mean by that? Obviously, this speaks a lot to open source nature

00:10:59.799 --> 00:11:10.919
of R that we all benefit from and code sharing, which really facilitates not just within department

00:11:10.919 --> 00:11:17.080
collaborations, right, but collaboration across function, across companies with John Johnson and

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:25.159
even beyond going into the community. So stat analysis automation that we're doing with Shiny

00:11:25.159 --> 00:11:31.239
apps and R markdown reports really allow us to release a lot of resources so we can go and

00:11:31.239 --> 00:11:37.559
explore other cutting edge technologies and bring innovative solutions to our drug discovery space.

00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:44.280
Now, immediate access to all the R packages, whether we're creating our own or using someone

00:11:44.280 --> 00:11:51.400
else's, facilitates innovative drug discovery statistics solutions that we create in our

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:57.719
department. And then something new that Johnson and Johnson haven't had before and had it into

00:11:57.719 --> 00:12:06.119
2020 is J&J hackathons that really bring together a lot of different employees from different parts

00:12:06.119 --> 00:12:11.719
of Johnson and Johnson, whether you're in consumer or medical devices or pharma, to work on solving

00:12:11.719 --> 00:12:16.760
some of the very interesting business problems. You know, and I'm proud to say that whoever

00:12:16.760 --> 00:12:24.679
participated in those hackathons from drug discovery statistics, we're all using R

00:12:24.679 --> 00:12:32.440
to solve those problems. So portfolio support, innovation, what else, right? Training. We've

00:12:32.440 --> 00:12:37.960
conducted a lot of smaller trainings that have to do with R, but I want to concentrate on two bigger

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:45.159
ones. So the first one in graphics with R, which have been talked about in previous years

00:12:45.159 --> 00:12:51.479
at the conferences at R and pharma and maybe others, where statistics and decision science

00:12:51.479 --> 00:12:58.280
department at Johnson put it together and led it with the aim of improving literacy in R

00:12:58.280 --> 00:13:04.679
programming among clinical statistician. So it was conducted to more than 100 clinical statisticians

00:13:04.679 --> 00:13:11.880
that went into the training and it was presented by external R experts. And a lot of them came from

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:17.000
drug discovery statistics group, which I belong to. So what we've done, we created a lot of

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:22.679
different homeworks on different topics that cover GG plot. We started with GG plot and it was the

00:13:22.679 --> 00:13:29.000
major intention, but the appetite just grew and we had to extend to R markdown, interactive plots,

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:35.400
tidyverse, dashboards. And I think we ended up with a small shiny app at the end, but we would

00:13:35.400 --> 00:13:42.039
deliver homework for people, for trainees, and then they would go into review and regroup session

00:13:42.039 --> 00:13:47.159
and brainstorm solutions. And then they would present the solution on the general forum and

00:13:47.159 --> 00:13:52.599
discuss that. And then the expert would sort of come with their tips and tricks presentations.

00:13:53.159 --> 00:14:01.239
So it worked really well and it was in 2019 at Janssen. So what happened last year, another

00:14:01.640 --> 00:14:09.799
training was designed and delivered, and that was led by quantitative sciences organization.

00:14:09.799 --> 00:14:16.039
And the aim there was to promote a shared foundation of quantitative literacy in machine

00:14:16.039 --> 00:14:23.159
learning space. That was a major, major effort, was 25 week course, again, presented by internal

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:30.840
expert. Those are statistician who have advanced degree in machine learning, including again,

00:14:30.840 --> 00:14:36.840
colleague of mine and myself, and they're mostly PhD, obviously, who presented content about

00:14:36.840 --> 00:14:41.159
machine learning that was structured in four different modules about statistical learning,

00:14:41.159 --> 00:14:47.239
classification, your supervised, unsupervised approaches, and was attended by hundreds of people

00:14:47.239 --> 00:14:54.200
from all over the company. So that's going outside of Janssen even. And the way we had it going was,

00:14:54.200 --> 00:15:00.280
you know, discussion of the theoretical part and then practical data application. And again,

00:15:00.280 --> 00:15:05.640
I'm proud to say that for the practical data application part, we use R entirely,

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:12.039
and we use R Markdown for all of our code. We had a standardized template that we all used,

00:15:12.039 --> 00:15:17.799
and we basically delivered all the solution in R Markdown. And that sort of goes in the

00:15:17.799 --> 00:15:22.440
repositories that a lot of trainees or people who attended or who didn't attend, but want to learn

00:15:22.440 --> 00:15:29.880
kind of can tap into now. So we talked about portfolio support, innovation training,

00:15:30.520 --> 00:15:37.640
but I think R also helps to build community, whether it's for R or R driven. So something

00:15:37.640 --> 00:15:43.799
that we have going on at Janssen, and this is the stuff that, you know, I'm kind of involved

00:15:43.799 --> 00:15:50.679
in participating in organizing, but maybe there are more, is something like a shiny day that we've

00:15:51.640 --> 00:15:58.200
been having for, I think, three last years, which is an annual event that is organized by Janssen

00:15:58.200 --> 00:16:05.719
Quantitative Sciences and Scientific Computing Operations in partnership with the Data and

00:16:05.719 --> 00:16:12.119
Statistics Society, which I co-lead with some other people, where we basically bring our shiny

00:16:12.119 --> 00:16:18.039
developers together at one or two day event. And, you know, back in pre-COVID time, we would

00:16:18.039 --> 00:16:23.880
actually meet on site, on different sites to kind of get to know each other and share some

00:16:23.880 --> 00:16:28.840
exciting work that we're doing in shiny application development space. But last year we had it

00:16:28.840 --> 00:16:34.840
obviously remote. So that has been of a great interest and the community there is growing.

00:16:35.640 --> 00:16:42.359
Also within J&J Data and Statistics Society, we do have workshops where we talk about R or,

00:16:42.359 --> 00:16:47.320
you know, discuss some of the methods developed in R. And, you know, the example there could be

00:16:48.039 --> 00:16:54.200
we're even having topics like using different software, but how do we plug in R in those

00:16:54.200 --> 00:16:58.840
softwares? And we had something about Tableau going on and, you know, how to bring R capabilities or

00:16:58.840 --> 00:17:04.760
how to connect R with Tableau and stuff like that. So we also have Yammer internal groups where our

00:17:04.760 --> 00:17:11.000
community is bubbling and growing, and I'm really happy to be part of it and see it grow. And I

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:15.319
think a separate community is something that we have around internal Bitbucket or, you know,

00:17:15.880 --> 00:17:22.359
internal GitHub where people share code and sort of create collaborations.

00:17:24.280 --> 00:17:30.119
Something else that we all love is hex stickers. So I love those like everybody else in this

00:17:30.119 --> 00:17:36.760
community. And I try to bring them in any app that I'm involved with. So some of the stickers

00:17:36.760 --> 00:17:42.760
that we've developed are kind of go for our shiny app that we created. And you see an example of

00:17:42.760 --> 00:17:47.959
the Enviva LD app that I put together and, you know, have a hex sticker for it. And then we put

00:17:47.959 --> 00:17:54.920
hex stickers together for different workshops or events that we have. You see a shiny day sticker

00:17:54.920 --> 00:18:01.640
and then some of the workshop that we had within that. And also we have a sticker for membership

00:18:01.640 --> 00:18:05.640
for Data and Statistics Society, which were actually in quite demand and we had to email

00:18:05.719 --> 00:18:14.599
them globally, which is great. So to summarize, R in Janssen drug discovery statistics today

00:18:14.599 --> 00:18:24.599
and tomorrow. So I think today we heavily rely on R and RStudio products. We use RStudio projects,

00:18:24.599 --> 00:18:31.560
R Markdown reports, shiny apps, R packages, which bring efficiencies and statistical rigor

00:18:31.640 --> 00:18:38.040
to our portfolio. They ensure reproducible and traceable research and also standardization

00:18:38.040 --> 00:18:45.079
and harmonization of methods, workflows, et cetera, and give us the capability to quickly

00:18:45.079 --> 00:18:52.920
adapt to changes. Then open source nature of R provides us with immediate access and opportunity

00:18:52.920 --> 00:18:58.760
to share our cutting edge and state-of-the-art statistical methodologies and also facilitates

00:18:58.760 --> 00:19:03.400
innovation and collaboration. And then we're growing our community internally

00:19:03.400 --> 00:19:09.000
through different platforms, workshops, internal events, and trainings. And we're trying to give

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:14.359
back to the community by having R packages on CRAN and presenting at different conferences.

00:19:16.920 --> 00:19:22.040
Some notes for future potential. I think we can keep building a larger R community,

00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:29.319
not just within our Janssen pharmaceutical space, but also go into other Johnson & Johnson sectors,

00:19:29.319 --> 00:19:35.640
whether it's medical devices or consumer finance, et cetera. So that's always a great thing to do.

00:19:36.520 --> 00:19:44.040
I think there are ways to work on sharing R code, again, across the enterprise, not just

00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:49.560
within sub-communities. So I think that would be something great to do in the future. And then

00:19:49.560 --> 00:19:54.599
enhancing internal R packages visibilities. This is something I also feel is important and

00:19:54.599 --> 00:20:01.000
we can work better there. And with that, I'm going to conclude and say thank you to some

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:07.719
of my colleagues who helped me to bounce back some of my ideas that I had for this presentation.

00:20:07.719 --> 00:20:14.599
And once again, thank you, R studio and people who organized this R in pharma conference for

00:20:14.599 --> 00:20:23.560
inviting me to speak. And here I'll conclude. Thank you so much.

